The `pandas` module seems to load the `pytz` module as a dependency, and some operations can raise a `pytz.NonExistentTimeError`. 

It appears that loading `pandas` as  shared module means that Python is unable to find that the `NonExistentTimeError` coming from `pandas` is the same as the one I've imported in my script to put in the `except` clause. If I do not use shared modules the code runs as expected.

A concrete example:

```java
import jep.Jep;
import jep.JepConfig;

public class ExceptionTypeTest {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        JepConfig jepConfig = new JepConfig();
        jepConfig.setInteractive(false);

        jepConfig.addSharedModules("pandas");  // comment out this line to see the expected print statements

        String script1 =
                        "import pandas as pd\n" +
                        "import pytz\n" +
                        "import sys\n" +
                        "d = pd.to_datetime('2017-10-15 00:00')\n";

        String script2 =
                        "try:\n" +
                        "\td.tz_localize('America/Sao_Paulo');\n" +  // this line is only caught properly without pandas as a shared module
                        "\traise pytz.NonExistentTimeError();\n" +   // this line is caught properly in both situations
                        "except pytz.NonExistentTimeError as e:\n" +
                        "\tprint('Saw exception');\n" +
                        "\tprint(type(e), e)\n" +
                        "\tsys.stdout.flush()\n";

        Jep jep = new Jep(jepConfig);
        for(String line : script1.split("\n")) {
            jep.eval(line);
        }
        jep.eval(script2);
        jep.close();
    }

}
```

I suppose this is a symptom of a more fundamental underlying issue with shared modules. 

